node.text:
Janet Blaser, 65, pays $420 per month to live in a 2-bedroom apartment in Mazatlán, Mexico. 

See inside the 1,100-square-foot apartment with 10-foot ceilings that is just a few minutes from one of her favorite beaches. 

Read more: https://cnb.cx/2VQvGhU

node.title: Inside a retiree's $420/month apartment by the beach in Mexico 🌴

node.text:
Steve, 39, and Courtney, 36, retired in 2016 with a combined net worth of $870,000. Watch as Kevin O'Leary, CNBC's new "Money Court" judge, shares his take on the couple's desert-dwelling lifestyle.

Read more: https://cnb.cx/2VLpkRj

node.title: Kevin O'Leary reacts to a millennial couple who retired early in their 30s

node.text:
Katie McRose, 26, and her wife Darian travel around Texas to sheer sheep, llamas and alpacas. They founded their business, Right Choice Shearing, in 2019. This year, they expect to bring in at least $80,000 servicing over 575 farms. 

Read more: https://cnb.cx/3AfkSJ2

node.title: Bringing in $80K a year shearing sheep in Texas.

node.text:
After being laid off from his corporate job during the pandemic, @therealchefoh decided to pursue his passion of cooking full-time. He now does around 4 parties per week and makes up to $14,000 per month.

Here's his story.

node.title: How 'Bling Empire's Kevin Kreider paid off $26,000 in debt

node.text: How a 26-year-old brings in up to $19K a month throwing parties.

node.title: ringing In Up To $19K A Month Throwing Parties

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 16, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says '×I don't wait for those things to find me:' How actress Kristen Bell combats her anxiety and depression at work #makeit'.

node.text:
Kristen Bell has spent the last two decades working in one of the world's most pressure-filled environments. Her biggest lesson for managing anxiety and depression: Don't let things fester.⁠
⁠
Along the way, Bell has picked up a few simple tactics to manage her own mental health. She shared her top three strategies in the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 16, 2021. May be an image of child and text that says 'Educational psychologist: If there's one skill you should teach your kids this is it #makeit'.

node.text:
There are numerous ways to help a child's learning and development, but one leading educational psychologist says unstructured "child-led" play is "intrinsically valuable" to fostering basic skills. ⁠
⁠
Read how it helps children to develop and why you shouldn't be as quick to stop "rough play" at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 16, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Your first job could significantly impact your heart's health later in life, a new study suggests #makeit'.

node.text:
While your first job as a teen or in your early 20s probably isn't a good predictor of your future success, it could be an indicator of your heart health later in life, a new study suggests. ⁠
⁠
Their findings: participants who were more educated and held managerial positions in their first few jobs had healthier hearts 20 years later than those who didn't.⁠
⁠
At the link in our bio, we're breaking down how researchers came to this conclusion, plus the part of the study that surprised them most.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 16, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, screen and text that says 'How to approach your return-to-office return concerns with your boss #makei'.

node.text:
A new survey found that 89% of employees still have lingering concerns about returning to the office. 😬⁠
⁠
CNBC Make It spoke with Alison Sullivan, a Glassdoor career trends expert about addressing those return-to-office concerns and how to approach the conversation with your boss (and colleagues). She shared 4 helpful tips at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 15, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, child and text that says 'A psychologist says parents of 'exceptionally resilient and successful' kids always do these 7 things: 'Yes, some are a little intense' #make'.

node.text:
In one expert's five-plus years of studying how to raise exceptional adults, he found that almost all of them, at a young age, developed the skills to maximize the physical, mental and social potential available to them. In most cases, their parents had an enormous impact in creating an environment that allowed them to thrive.⁠ ⁠ ⁠
⁠
From creating a culture of striving and excellence to encouraging self-confidence, check out 7 things that parents of exceptionally resilient and successful kids always do, in the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 15, 2021. May be an image of 2 people and text that says 'This is the fastest path to becoming a millionaire-but -but it's also the hardest, says money expert EXIT åmake'.

node.text:
What specific things are the rich doing every day that the rest of us aren't? Is there a specific formula for accumulating extreme wealth? 🤔⁠
⁠
According to Tom Corley's "Rich Habits" study, in which he spent five years observing and documenting the daily activities of 233 wealthy individuals (all had at least $160,000 in annual gross income and $3.2 million in net assets), he found that there are four main paths to becoming a multimillionaire. ⁠
⁠
Read why "The Dreamers path" is said to be number one at the link in our bio.

Janet Blaser, 65, pays $420 per month to live in a 2-bedroom apartment in Mazatlán, Mexico. 

See inside the 1,100-square-foot apartment with 10-foot ceilings that is just a few minutes from one of her favorite beaches. 

Read more: https://cnb.cx/2VQvGhU

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 15, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Chairman of GameStop and co-founder of Chewy: This is the side hustle I'd start now to make extra money #makeit'.

node.text:
In 2011, at age 25, Ryan Cohen co-founded Chewy.com. In 2017, Cohen and his co-founder sold Chewy to PetSmart for $3.35 billion. ⁠
⁠
But if Cohen needed extra cash today, he would go back to his roots to create a side hustle. "I would go door-to-door searching for local companies that have no web presence [and] I would offer to build them websites," he tells CNBC Make It. ⁠
⁠
Read why this type of work is in high demand, plus Cohen's advice for boosting finances, at the link in our bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'The 10 U.S. states with the most credit card debt CVV VESL SYELL #makeit'.

node.text:
Americans started 2021 with nearly $900 billion in credit card debt. And that amount is projected to increase by $60 billion by the end of the year, according to WalletHub. 💳⁠
⁠
From Alaska to New Hampshire, check out the 10 states where individuals owe the most on their credit card balances in the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 14, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'These are the 5 most valuable skills to learn right now, says futurist and where to find free online courses #makeit'.

node.text:
With rising geopolitical concerns and technology advancing faster than ever, continuous learning is crucial to staying ahead of the curve.⁠ ⁠
⁠
From futuristic thinking to emotional intelligence, we spoke to an expert about the 5 most valuable skills to master, along with the best free online courses to help you build upon them, in the link in bio.

node.text:
Since starting to accept dogecoin as payment for merchandise in March, the Dallas Mavericks organization has seen substantial sales made with the meme-inspired cryptocurrency, according to team owner Mark Cuban. ⁠
⁠
Read why Cuban says it has a unique use case over other cryptocurrencies at the link in bio.
